snippet.textDisplay:
Alfa is missing an Estate for the European market - in which they had been strong enough due to the 156 and 159 Sportwagon (60-70% of them being a Sportwagon). They essentially miss their target here by pointing at the Stelvio as estate replacement - which is a totally different car category. Seeing the low sales of the Stelvio, but also the Giulia I personally see Alfa not understanding market demands, which seems to be the source of that being their management.
They made the Giulia a nice car - not as iconic as 156 and 159, but technically much more refined - but ignored where they had strong sales.
I wish Alfa Romeo good luck, but I currently don't see them succeed with their existing strategy.
